article.description: The Nets looked completely inept in a 83-71 setback to the Houston Rockets that was not nearly as close as the score.
article.headline: Sluggish Nets score just eight second-quarter points

images.name: Ming Yao 030308 inline
images.caption: Houston's Yao Ming had four swats to go with 12 points and 10 rebounds.

article.linkText: Rockets send free-falling Nets to fourth straight loss
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Just when the New Jersey Nets thought their shooting couldn't get any worse, it did. Cuttino Mobley scored 18 points and Steve Francis had 17 as the Houston Rockets took advantage of a record-low first half by the Nets for a 83-71 victory Saturday night. The Nets lost for the fourth straight time and for the seventh time in eight games. New Jersey scored eight points in the second quarter and 24 in the first half, both franchise lows. New Jersey's previous halftime low was 27 points Jan. 12, 1996 against Philadelphia. They scored nine second quarter points twice, most recently April 14, 2002 at Toronto. "We didn't have any energy or effort,'' Nets coach Byron Scott said. "I don't know what happened. We played the first half like the season was over. The second half we played hard, but we still didn't make the shots.'' The Nets finished at 36 percent from the field. Jason Kidd, the team's leading scorer, shot only 3-for-12 for six points. "We've got to get back to who we are,'' Scott said. "We're a better team than what we're playing, especially tonight. I thought the way we practiced yesterday we would have more effort tonight, but it didn't happen.'' The Rockets held a 44-24 lead at the half and it didn't get any better for the Nets in the third quarter. Houston led 62-44 to start the fourth. Yao Ming added 12 points and 10 rebounds for the Rockets and Glen Rice scored 12 off the bench. "We predicted they were going to use a lot of the backdoor play,'' Yao said. "We planned to have the center come and help any time they used that, so we were able to stop their most effective play.'' Kenyon Martin led the Nets with 16 points. Richard Jefferson and Jason Collins each had 10. "This was a very big win for us,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. "We worked in our practice yesterday on some of the things they do. They have a backdoor cut off play where they get a lot of layups. "We did a good job of getting ready for that. I can't tell you how pleased I am with our defense for being ready for that.'' The Rockets tried going inside to Yao early in the first quarter and when that didn't work, Yao started hitting jump shots and Eddie Griffin helped out with nine points, including a 3-pointer at the first-quarter buzzer for a 23-16 lead. "It was good to be able to get our defense up and pressure them,'' Francis said. "It helped us get a lot of shots. Their leader (Kidd) was hurt. I don't know what was wrong with him, but that doesn't mean we didn't do a good job on defense.'' The Nets' shooting has been on a downward spiral since the All-Star break. Saturday continued the decline. "I really don't know what happened,'' Kerry Kittles said. "That's what they were giving us and we took it. We don't have any sharpness, confidence or energy. It's just not there.'' Is this the season's low point? "I think that's obvious,'' Kittles said. "Anyone can see that we're not right. This is not a good feeling. We want to have some swagger and we don't have that right now.''

Game notes
The Rockets should be rested. They've played one game over a six-day stretch of March 6-11. ... Jason Kidd's career high of 43 points came at Compaq Center on March 29, 2001 when he played for the Phoenix Suns. ... Hall of Famer Calvin Murphy scored a Rockets franchise record 57 points against the Nets at Compaq Center in 1978. It still stands as the most points scored in an NBA game in the state of Texas.
